generif.text: Observational study of gene-disease association. (HuGE Navigator)
mutations in the gene encoding mitochondrial arginyl-tRNA synthetase, RARS2, may have a role in pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 6 [case report]
Molecular investigations of RARS2 disclosed the c.25A>G/p.I9V and the c.1586+3A>T in family A.
Mutations in the RARS2 promoter are likely to represent a new causal mechanism of pontocerebellar hypoplasia.
RARS2 gene mutations can cause a metabolic neurodegenerative disease manifesting primarily as early onset epileptic encephalopathies with post-natal microcephaly, without pontocerebellar hypoplasia.
Characteristic neuroradiological abnormalities of PCH6 such as vermis and cerebellar hypoplasia and progressive pontocerebellar atrophy may be missing in patients with RARS2 mutations
Whole-exome sequencing in adult patients with developmental and epileptic encephalopathy: It is never too late.
Novel RARS2 Variants: Updating the Diagnosis and Pathogenesis of Pontocerebellar Hypoplasia Type 6.
Clinical and genetic analysis of infants with pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 6 caused by RARS2 variations.

name: arginyl-tRNA synthetase 2, mitochondrial
summary: This nuclear gene encodes a protein that localizes to the mitochondria, where it catalyzes the transfer of L-arginine to its cognate tRNA, an important step in translation of mitochondrially-encoded proteins. Defects in this gene are a cause of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 6 (PCH6). Alternative splicing results in multiple transcript variants. [provided by RefSeq, Jan 2016].
